#Lyrics
Eternal Father, strong to save, Whose arm hath bound the restless wave, Who bidd'st the mighty ocean deep Its own appointed limits keep, O hear us when we cry to thee For those in peril on the sea!  2. O Christ! Whose voice the waters heard And hushed their raging at thy word, Who walkedst on the foaming deep, And calm amidst its rage didst sleep, O hear us when we cry to thee, For those in peril on the sea!  3. Most Holy Spirit! Who didst brood Upon the chaos dark and rude, And bid its angry tumult cease, And give, for wild confusion, peace, O hear us when we cry to thee For those in peril on the sea!  4. O Trinity of love and power, Our people shield in danger's hour; From rock and tempest, fire and foe, Guard them where'er they may go; Thus evermore shall rise to Thee Glad hymns of praise from land and sea.  5. Eternal Father, grant, we pray, To all Marines, both night and day, The courage, honor, strength, and skill Their land to serve, thy law fulfill; Be thou the shield forevermore From every peril to the Corps.  6. Lord, guard and guide the ones who fly Through the great spaces in the sky. Be with them always in the air, In darkening storms or sunlight fair.

#Citations and References

Words: Stanzas 1–4: William Whiting, 1860. Translation/text from United States Naval Academy Chapel. Stanzas 5–6: additional service stanzas, source: United States Naval Academy Chapel (usna.edu/Chapel/navyhymn.php), public domain.
Music: 'Melita' John Bacchus Dykes, 1861.
Setting: "Hymns Ancient and Modern", 1861.
copyright: public domain. This score is a part of the Open Hymnal Project, 2006 Revision.

Note on text variants: Stanzas 1–3 follow the USNA Chapel text (usna.edu), which differs in small details from the Open Hymnal Project version — notably stanza 2 "didst sleep" (Christ asleep in the boat, Mark 4:38) vs "didst keep" in some printings; stanza 3 "Most Holy Spirit" and "chaos dark" vs "O Holy Spirit" and "waters dark". The USNA wording is closer to Whiting's original. Stanza 4 (Trinity) retained from the Open Hymnal Project version; it is absent from some abbreviated printings. Stanza 6 (Aviators) is given as 4 lines per the USNA source; the full 6-line form adds the refrain couplet "O hear us when we cry to thee / For those in peril in the air!"

